message.content: For any polynomial $f$ with natural number coefficients, any natural number $n$, and any two functions $a: \text{Fin}\, n \to \mathbb{R}$ and $b: \text{Fin}\, n \to \mathbb{N}$, if $b$ is injective, then evaluating the polynomial $f$ at 1 equals the product of the images of $b$ divided by $n!$.

For any polynomial \( f \) with natural number coefficients, any natural number \( n \), any function \( a \) from the finite type with \( n \) elements to the real numbers, and any injective function \( b \) from the finite type with \( n \) elements to the natural numbers, the evaluation of \( f \) at 1 equals the product of the values of \( b \) over all elements of the finite type divided by \( n! \).

The theorem states that for any polynomial $f$ with natural number coefficients, a natural number $n$, and two functions $a : \mathrm{Fin}\, n \to \mathbb{R}$ and $b : \mathrm{Fin}\, n \to \mathbb{N}$ where $b$ is injective, the evaluation of $f$ at 1 equals the product of the values of $b$ over all indices in $\mathrm{Fin}\, n$, divided by $n!$.

The theorem states that for any polynomial $f$ with natural number coefficients, any natural number $n$, and any functions $a: \text{Fin } n \to \mathbb{R}$ and $b: \text{Fin } n \to \mathbb{N}$, if $b$ is injective, then evaluating the polynomial $f$ at $1$ gives the product of the values of $b$ over the factorial of $n$, i.e., $\text{Polynomial.eval } 1 f = \frac{\prod_{i \in \text{Fin } n} b(i)}{n!}$.

The theorem states that for any polynomial $f$ with natural number coefficients, a natural number $n$, and two functions $a$ and $b$ from the finite set $\text{Fin}\, n$ to the reals and natural numbers respectively, if $b$ is injective, then evaluating $f$ at $1$ equals the product of $b(i)$ for all $i$ in $\text{Fin}\, n$ divided by $n!$, the factorial of $n$.

The theorem states that for any polynomial $f$ with natural number coefficients, any natural number $n$, and any injective function $b$ from the finite type $\text{Fin}\, n$ to the natural numbers, evaluating $f$ at 1 is equal to the product of the values of $b$ divided by $n!$, i.e., $\text{Polynomial.eval}\, 1\, f = \frac{\prod_{i : \text{Fin}\, n} b(i)}{n!}$.

The theorem states that for any polynomial $f$ with natural number coefficients, any natural number $n$, and any injections $a : \text{Fin} \, n \to \mathbb{R}$ and $b : \text{Fin} \, n \to \mathbb{N}$, if $b$ is injective, then evaluating $f$ at 1 yields the product of the images of $b$ divided by $n!$, i.e., $\text{Polynomial.eval} \, 1 \, f = \frac{\prod_{i : \text{Fin} \, n} b(i)}{n!}$.

The theorem states that for any polynomial \( f \) with natural number coefficients, any natural number \( n \), and any functions \( a : \text{Fin}\ n \to \mathbb{R} \) and \( b : \text{Fin}\ n \to \mathbb{N} \), if \( b \) is injective, then evaluating \( f \) at 1 equals the product of the values \( b(i) \) for \( i \) in \( \text{Fin}\ n \) divided by \( n! \).

For any polynomial $f$ with natural number coefficients, any natural number $n$, and any injective function $b$ from the finite set $\{0, 1, \ldots, n-1\}$ to the natural numbers, evaluating $f$ at $1$ equals the product over all elements $b(i)$ divided by $n!$.

For any polynomial $f$ with natural number coefficients, a natural number $n$, and injective functions $a$ from the finite set $\{0, 1, \ldots, n-1\}$ to the real numbers and $b$ from the finite set $\{0, 1, \ldots, n-1\}$ to the natural numbers, the evaluation of $f$ at 1 equals the product of the values of $b$ divided by $n!$.
